{
  "family": "Pinner Reaction",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CC#N",
      "CCO"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "CC(=[NH2+])OCC.[Cl-]"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "Cl"
    ],
    "rationale": "This example shows the formation of an imino ether hydrochloride salt (a Pinner salt) from a simple aliphatic nitrile (acetonitrile) and an alcohol (ethanol) in the presence of dry hydrogen chloride. This represents the core transformation of the Pinner reaction, which is the acid-catalyzed addition of an alcohol to a nitrile. The reactants and product are simple, acyclic, and clearly illustrate the key bond formations (C-O) and changes in functional groups (nitrile to imino ether salt).",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The use of simple, acyclic aliphatic substrates (acetonitrile, ethanol) avoids overlap with reactions involving aromatic rings (e.g., Friedel-Crafts, Gattermann), complex rearrangements, or other named reactions that might involve nitriles in a different context. The product is the characteristic imino ether salt, which is specific to the Pinner reaction and its direct variants, rather than downstream hydrolysis products like esters, which could collide with Fischer esterification."
  }
}
